???: [――Just like you, I am a complete failure of a girl.]

Aldebaran would never forget the somber expression upon the Witch’s visage as she spoke those words.

And so, he had thought.

Did even the Witch, with a face that seemed to know just about anything and everything concerning this world’s providence, with demeanor that seemed to disseminate the roots of knowledge through every nook and cranny of this world, who conducted herself with an air of understanding every aspect of the universe, did she too have moments in which she grieved her own powerlessness?

Witch: [Of course I do. If you would like an example, then your very existence… the very fact that you are currently like this, is proof that I was lacking, after all.]

Hearing that, Aldebaran’s feelings were complicated.

Within Aldebaran, this Witch was a great existence, and though he was loath to admit it, she was even a tremendous one. Although there were few to whom he could compare her, she was someone who always felt greater than any comparison.

For that Witch to consider herself a complete failure, was of no joy to him whatsoever.

Only, if the Witch had been bereft of such self-acknowledgement, her current relationship with Aldebaran would not exist. If the Witch had been in any position to not deem herself a complete failure――,

Witch: [Then, you and I would have simply remained in our rightful places. You are free to daydream about a future that did not unfold in such a manner, but unfortunately, you ended up being dealt the worst fate of all. Though I am sorry to say, it was rather fortuitous for myself.]

That deliberately wicked phrasing seemed to be an equal blend of the Witch’s humor and the Witch’s sincerity. As for which one it actually was, he could not tell.

After all, always boasting of her inability to comprehend the human heart, the Witch’s true feelings were unclear to even Aldebaran, who had been in her company for so long, leaving him with nothing to latch onto.

But, supposing the Witch’s words were correct, it was rather strange.

After all, even though the alignment of the stars was at its absolute worst for Aldebaran in his current circumstances, he did not consider his days with the Witch to be a misfortune.

Though certainly, with her putting him through the experience of being killed a million times under the guise of being a trial, calling him by a name he disliked even after objecting to it in disagreement, there was no doubt that these circumstances were far removed from any ordinary notion of happiness.

Witch: [To think you could find value in living alongside a complete failure of a Witch, you are truly a pitiful child.]

This was a complex muttering, containing both self-deprecation alongside a firm deprecation of the other party.

However, Aldebaran would not fail to hear the gentle timbre that could not be fully concealed therein.

Even if they were meager, even if they were easily lost in the mix, even if they were difficult to understand, earnest emotions did dwell within the Witch. Searching for evidence as a basis to believe that, was a pastime of Aldebaran’s.

In truth, he did not really know for sure. It might have just been a misunderstanding or a misconception.

What mattered was how Aldebaran felt; the Witch’s true intentions were her own to keep. ――What was the truth for Aldebaran, was for Aldebaran alone.

Witch: [The way you separate those things is remarkably reminiscent. As expected, the thing known as influence is not to be trifled with.]

Narrowing her black eyes, fiddling with her white bangs, thus spoke the Witch.

While simultaneously looking past Aldebaran to somebody else, and at herself reflected within Aldebaran’s irises, the Witch muttered those words reminiscently.

Influence, it was only natural for such a thing to exist. In birth, and in upbringing.

In Aldebaran, and in the Witch.

Failure, inadequacy, imperfection. ――Was that past of hers really so shameful for the Witch?

Was it a curse for him to think that thanks to it having turned out that way, his days with the Witch were able to continue?

If only one thing could be said, it was――,

Witch: [――Aldebaran.]

A reunion spanning a decade for Aldebaran, and stretching across four centuries for the other party, when the figure of the Witch―― nay, of the Witch of Greed, present amidst familiar scenery, was one that contradicted the complete failure she had spoken about back on that day, Aldebaran was overcome with unbearable feelings of loss and despair.

△▼△▼△▼△

――Fiddling with the metal fixtures of his black helmet, Aldebaran surveyed the situation.

Before his eyes, having used the almost divine colossal anchor of ice as a landmark, the lineup of personnel boldly squared off against Aldebaran.

The group opposing him was one centered around Filóre―― no, around Felt, so Aldebaran made no effort to question the meaning of them having assembled here.

Even without needing to ask, he understood. ――Roy and Heinkel had been defeated.

He could not imagine that even “Aldebaran” had been defeated, but since the Dragon had not hastened here, it seemed that it was being contained through some means.

On top of defeating the Sin Archbishop of Gluttony, even if he may have been restricted with his Authority and with the “no-killing” rule, the fact that they had even devised a countermeasure for the Divine Dragon was quite honestly beyond Aldebaran’s imagination.

Just what sort of stratagem had they prepared; he would likely not get an answer even if he asked, but――,

×　　×　　×

――Two-hundred and forty-six.

Aldebaran: [――No matter how you slice it, a Witch Factor’s just way too far for your resolve, Lil’ Miss Petra.]

???: [――Hk.]

At Aldebaran’s straightforward remark, an air of tension ran through Felt’s group.

The one whose cheeks had stiffened the most was naturally Petra, given that her name had been called out. From their perspective, Petra’s Authority was their trump card, something that was supposed to have been top secret.

In fact, that policy had been firmly shared by all their personnel.

Yet, even the most iron of hearts could not remain unfazed before an unforeseen stab.

In response to Aldebaran’s questions, everyone had kept up appearances, but through even the slightest shifts in gaze or attention, he would just keep testing over and over again, relentlessly probing in those directions. As a result, by pursuing the minute differences in their reactions, Aldebaran had arrived at the answer he desired, standing steadfast before him. ――Though, he had been considerably shocked when it turned out to be Petra, who had taken in a Witch Factor.

Aldebaran: [In the first place, I predicted that when either Lil’ Miss Petra or Lil’ Miss Meili read that, they’d be completely incapable of returning to the front lines.]

Having sealed Natsuki Subaru and Beatrice away at the Pleiades Watchtower, and after getting Garfiel and Ezzo out of the way, Aldebaran had let Petra and Meili go without any harm.

Not only was that because there had been no need to eliminate them, it was a stratagem in anticipation of what was to follow.

In order to keep Reinhard contained, it had been absolutely necessary to manifest the Witch of Envy.

As the trigger for that, Aldebaran had selected Petra and Meili as the candidates to read Natsuki Subaru’s Book of the Dead. In reality, the intrusion of the Witch of Envy had granted Aldebaran a way out from his prolonged fight against Reinhard, successfully eliminating the greatest obstacle to his plan.

However――,

Aldebaran: […Even though reading anyone’s book usually has a high chance of causing a mental breakdown, to think she was able to endure reading Natsuki Subaru’s Book of the Dead.]

A precedent, did exist. ――Aldebaran happened to know that all too well, but even so, the reason he did not believe that anyone could accomplish that same feat was due to the absolute nature of Death.

The Book of the Dead belonging to Natsuki Subaru was a special-grade cursed object that, depending on the situation, could be used as a trump card to defeat a higher-level opponent. It was highly unlikely that there were many who could face it without having their hearts shattered.

Aldebaran: […Or rather, I’ve got a bad habit of underestimating others.]

Regardless of what Aldebaran thought, it was a matter of fact that Petra was now standing here.

Not only had she avoided having her heart shattered by the impact of reading the Book of the Dead, she had even gone so far as to perform the outrageous act of housing a Witch Factor within herself. In all likelihood, the experience of reading the Book of the Dead had led Petra to doing so.

???: [――There is nobody who can defeat you, you whom I created.]

Flashing through the back of his mind, those words of the Witch were intended to rouse Aldebaran’s spirits, never to fill him with arrogance or cause him to stumble.

If he got that mixed up, Aldebaran would lose the Witch for good this time. ――This time for good, he would lose the Witch who, reduced to the Witch of Greed, had lost the heart she had certainly once possessed.

Aldebaran: [――In the end, I guess I just can’t leave fate in the hands of others.]

Suppressing the sentimentality gripping his heart with deep breaths, Aldebaran faced forward.

The enemy was strong, the obstacles many, he was bereft of allies, with nothing to be proud of―― even so, he decided to proceed.

That instant――,

???: [――ORAHHHHH!!]

――Ablaze with rage, the stout fist of the golden tiger furiously drove into Aldebaran’s head.

△▼△▼△▼△

――God, Buddah, Od Lagna. For as long as I live, I hereby vow to never partake in celebrations.

△▼△▼△▼△

――Sixty-one people in total.

After the conclusion against Roy Alphard of Gluttony, that was what composed the Aldebusters―― the combined strength of the Emilia Camp and the Felt Camp, reorganized for the final battle against Al.

Right after that fierce battle had ended, when the team was reorganized without taking a moment to breathe, Petra could not help but feel gratitude and admiration that so many still chose to remain. However, that was by no means condemning those who did not accompany the reorganized team.

???: [After all, neither Otto nor Meili can be pushed any further than that.]

Just as the Imaginary Subaru said, for Otto and Meili―― both individuals who had served as deciding factors in the clash against Gluttony, withdrawing from the front lines was necessary; it was only natural for Otto, whose Memories had been eaten, and Meili, who had vehemently exhausted herself by overworking her Divine Protection to detain the Black Serpent.

And it was not just them. Roy’s trump card, unveiled in the eleventh hour, using the Authority of Gluttony to force them to relive pains of the past, had abraded some of their minds to the limit. Unlike wounds to the body, abrasions to the heart could not be easily restored even with Petra’s Compression. But then again, Meili had still continued to insist that her recovery time be Compressed so that she could return to the front lines, but――,

Petra: [If you took out an advance payment on your life, Subaru wouldn’t be too happy, you know?]

And so, persuaded by Petra, Meili had reluctantly, truly so very reluctantly, accepted her withdrawal from the battlefield.

To be honest, Petra’s maiden circuitry felt a subtle discomfort upon witnessing Meili’s attitude in response to a persuasion that cited Subaru, but since it was the result of her own actions, she did not speak much of it.

Moreover, she also had the duty of keeping an eye out for the Black Serpent that had been summoned by Gluttony, having vanished after combat had concluded. Petra felt apologetic that she was unable to grant her a complete rest.

“Subaru”: [We’ve got no choice but to have the capable ones to fill in where they can. With that said, there’re still some crazy guys who’ll rush into the most high-risk situations even without their memories.]

Petra: [It’s incredible, isn’t it? You can’t help but think that Otto-san’s that way, even without his memories.]

“Subaru”: [I guess it’s just his innate disposition? He might be a risk junkie.]

If the person in question were to hear that remark, whether he had memories or not, he would likely retort in a deeply emotional tone, “Could you please refrain from saying such disreputable things about me!?”; but, there was no avoiding him being thought of in such a manner.

Either way, Gluttony had firmly weakened their precious fighting strength, limiting the cards in their hand for the climax. She was glad for Garfiel’s return, but the fact that they could not devote the entirety of their forces to Emilia and Rem was regrettable for both Petra and “Subaru”.

But, even so――,

Petra: [――We’re going to win, Subaru.]

“Subaru”: [Yeah, let’s go and win. After all, we can’t let everything we’ve built up to this point be for nothing.]

△▼△▼△▼△

――God, Buddha, Od Lagna. For as long as I live, I hereby vow to never speak of my dreams to another.

△▼△▼△▼△

Aldebaran: [――In the end, I guess I just can’t leave fate in the hands of others.]

An offhanded remark, yet with a tone carrying resolve, that which was spoken by Al had served as the signal.

Garfiel: [――ORAHHHHH!!]

With the raging Garfiel at the vanguard, the Aldebusters simultaneously sprung into action.

Keeping her eyes trained over those movements, Petra grasped her hands tightly over her chest.

――With the ice anchor Emilia had fired as a landmark, Petra had Compressed the distance to the current location with the Aldebusters in tow, barring Al’s path once more.

In all honesty, the fact that Emilia and Rem were not present, and the fact that the kunoichi assigned to accompany Al, who had unexpectedly been carried off with him, was nowhere to be found was certainly a cause for concern, but,

“Subaru”: [――Al’s side has no reason to lift their no-killing restriction.]

Using that as reassurance, perhaps that was placing a bit too much hope in their opponent’s abilities and convictions.

But, when considering Al’s fighting style with his Authority of “Turning Back Time” until this point, that was the foundation. Since his Authority was far too strong, in a sense, Al had gotten away with being underestimated by his opponents up until now.

And that premise, even now that his allies had been stripped away from him, ultimately would not change.

Garfiel: [Gahguh-!]

Having rushed straight ahead without any preparatory movements, Garfiel raised his voice in pain.

The reason for this was his collision into a stone slab that had suddenly appeared along his trajectory. Having slammed his face into the stone slab that had preempted his initial strike, Garfiel’s body rolled over mid-air. And slipping past from underneath Garfiel, Al moved to intercept the fighting strength which followed after the golden tiger.

Coming after him was the trio of Ram, Flam, and Grassis.

“Subaru”: [Oddly enough, it’s the pink-haired sisters! Well then, how’s it gonna go!?]

△▼△▼△▼△

――Thirty-seven.

Intercepting Garfiel’s rush with a stone slab, he slipped underneath as the former reeled backwards.

The timing had been unexpectedly tight. If the stone slab was deployed too early, it would have been easily pulverized, and deploying it too late would allow Garfiel to pass right by it. Perfecting the necessary timing to strike him in the face, he put it into practice.

Garfiel: [Gahguh-!]

Hearing the cry of pain behind him, Aldebaran charged forward as three shadows swooped down upon him.

He was flanked on his left and right by Flam and her sister, in sync with Ram who came at him from an upward diagonal. He could expect that sort of high precision coordination between twins, but Ram’s ability to match them on first sight highlighted the abnormality of this teamup.

Thereupon――,

Aldebaran: [Lil’ Miss Rem was crushed flat at those cliffs back there.]

Ram: [She wasn’t. Do not underestimate Ram and Rem’s sisterly love.]

Neutralized by the sisters’ synesthesia, the venom in his words failed to exhibit any effectiveness.

Given her lack of discomposure, there was likely no falsehood in Ram’s statement. Inferring how that signified Rem’s safety, as well as the unknown fate of Yae, it merely ended up serving as venom against himself.

However――,

Aldebaran: [――Earth Brand Arts.]

Using the Mana coming to him via his pathway with the Dragon, Aldebaran surrounded himself with swords of stone. In order to avoid the tips of the swords shooting up from the ground one after another, the twins deftly maneuvered their bodies to perform evasions, yielding a momentary delay that shifted their three-way coordination into a solo-attack from Ram.

With Ram singled out, he grabbed one of his stone daos and thrust it toward her head-on――,

Ram: [That’s fine. I’ll be borrowing it.]

Having scooped up his sword with wind magic, Ram slammed it right into the side of his jaw.

×　　×　　×

――Ninety-one.

Ram: [That’s fine. I’ll―― not be borrowing it.]

Declaring so, Ram allowed the stone sword she had pulled toward her with wind to pass by, brittly crumbling as it flew past her; as she had failed to take the sword, Aldebaran delivered a blow unto her.

Ram parried that blow with wind from her wand, skillfully controlling the wind  currents to build air pressure and push past the clash of blades. Grabbing her leg with a stone prosthetic, he hurled her behind him while being bombarded by an onslaught of wind blades.

Ram: [――Hk.]

Leaving Ram gritting her teeth behind him, Aldebaran pressed onward, and the delayed sisters of Flam and Grassis swooped down on him once more.

Readying himself for their approaching agility that could not be underestimated on account of their youth, Aldebaran spread out his real right arm and artificial left arm, and roused a surging wave of sand to clear away everything in the one-hundred and eighty degree field of view in front of him.

The girls were engulfed by the billowing sand, becoming encaged within the ground――,

???: [――Warrior ta Yin Six! Magician ta Wind Five! King ta Flowers Eight!]

A surging force abruptly slammed into him from the front, plunging him into the sea of swords he had forged behind himself.

×　　×　　×

――One-hundred and twelve.

???: [――Warrior ta Yin Six! Magician ta Wind Five! King ta Flowers Eight!]

As soon heard it, he forcibly closed in his outstretched arms, fixing the muzzle of the wave of sand directly in front of him―― the large bearded man who appeared there a beat later basked in the billowing wave, ending up in the same predicament as Flam and Grassis.

Thereby averting that misfortune, Aldebaran would attempt to overcome the enemies as he jumped out diagonally――,

???: [UL GOA!!]

Still in his mid-air leap, he was struck by an unavoidable fastball of flame, scorching his insides.

×　　×　　×

――One-hundred and forty-six.

???: [UL GOA!!]

After trapping the twins and the large man in sand, he deliberately delayed his advance in response to the approaching fireball. Instead, what ended up basking in the inferno was a poorly made clay doll that Aldebaran had manifested in the spur of the moment―― a poor knockoff of the magic Emilia had used to recreate Natsuki Subaru with ice.

The fireball aimed to strike Aldebaran’s head as he leaped forward, so amidst a combat requiring split-second decisions, it was easily baited by the poorly made earthen doll.

???: [Wha!?]

The skinny man who had casted the spell, with his mean-looking eyes and tongue piercing, gasped at Aldebaran’s countermeasure.

So long as he was not an expert magician, he would not be able to unleash Ul-tier magic in rapid succession. Flipping up his artificial middle finger to that expression of shock, Aldebaran moved to advance even further this time――,

???: [――Fire!!]

From an oblique trajectory behind him, a light was fired as a shock wave that speared through Aldebaran’s back; the luminosity of the corona that seemed to scorch the world painted even his consciousness white.

×　　×　　×

――One-hundred and forty-seven.

???: [――Fire!!]

Turning to face the direction of the gallant war cry, Aldebaran recognized the identity of the perpetrator as Felt, baring her high canines in a valiant expression, in her grasp the magic staff that sourced the beam of light.

That was the Meteor known as the Star Staff, something the Witch had once used during her lifetime to make even the Divine Dragon cry; in other words, it was one of his mentor’s loose ends.

Aldebaran: [For Teacher to be getting in my way here, what kinda damn bug is this?]

At the untiring challenge that would stretch endlessly on ahead, at the wall he would have no choice but surmount at all costs, and at the fact that it was something originating from none other than the very Witch who had guided Aldebaran’s path, a tinge of melancholy burgeoned in his heart.

As Aldebaran contemplated, the white light mercilessly engulfed him once again.

Well then――,

×　　×　　×

――One-hundred and forty-eight.

Felt: [――Fire!!]

――The approach of this white light, just how on earth could it be conquered?

△▼△▼△▼△

